

Q3: Where can we use BlockingQueue in real-time scenarios?

        1. Scenario 1 — Bulk Upload Processing:

           1. Suppose we have a service where admin uploads Excel file with 10,000 dealer records.
           2. If we process all 10,000 in single thread, API will timeout. So instead —
              Thread-1 (producer) reads Excel rows and puts them into BlockingQueue.
           3. Thread-2,3,4 (consumers) pick from queue and save to database.
           4. If consumers are slow, producer automatically waits (queue full). If producer is slow,
           5. consumers automatically wait (queue empty). No data loss, no race condition.

           6. Code snippet:

                              BlockingQueue<String> queue = new ArrayBlockingQueue<>(500);
                              queue.put("dealer-row-1");
                              String row = queue.take();
                              dealershipLocationRepository.save(row);

        2. Scenario 2 — Rate-Limited External API Calls:
        
           1. Suppose we need to call MDP API for 500 dealer codes, but MDP has rate limit of 10 req/sec.
           2. We put all 500 dealer codes into a BlockingQueue. Then 3 worker threads pick one by one
           3. from queue, call MDP, and process response. When queue is empty, workers stop automatically.
           4. No busy-waiting, no polling loop needed.

           5. Code snippet:

                              BlockingQueue<String> queue = new LinkedBlockingQueue<>();
                              queue.put("SAP1001");
                              String dealerCode = queue.take();
                              mdpDealerService.getActiveDealerDataOrElseThrow(dealerCode, locationType);

        3. Scenario 3 — Log Processing / Event Pipeline:
        
           1. Application generates thousands of log events per second. Instead of writing to file/DB directly 
              (which is slow and blocks main thread), events go into BlockingQueue.      
           2. A separate background thread picks events from queue and writes to file/DB in batches. Main thread never 
              gets blocked by I/O.   

           3. Code snippet:

                              BlockingQueue<String> queue = new LinkedBlockingQueue<>(1000);
                              queue.put("dealer updated successfully");
                              String logEvent = queue.take();
                              auditLogService.saveLog(logEvent);

        4. Scenario 4 — Order Processing in E-Commerce:
        
           1. Customer places order -> order goes into BlockingQueue. Multiple worker threads pick orders and process
              them (payment, inventory, notification). If order volume is high, workers are
              busy and queue fills up.  
           2. If queue reaches capacity, the system naturally applies backpressure (new orders wait until 
              workers free up).   

           3. Code snippet:

                              BlockingQueue<String> queue = new ArrayBlockingQueue<>(200);
                              queue.put("order-101");
                              String orderId = queue.take();
                              orderService.process(orderId);

        5. Scenario 5 — Thread Pool Internals:
           
           1. Java's ThreadPoolExecutor itself uses BlockingQueue internally. 
           2. When we submit a task to thread pool and all threads are busy, the task sits in the BlockingQueue
              waiting for a free thread.      
           3. This is why when we create ThreadPoolExecutor, we pass a BlockingQueue as constructor parameter.   

           4. Code snippet:

                              BlockingQueue<Runnable> queue = new LinkedBlockingQueue<>(500);
                              ThreadPoolExecutor executor = new ThreadPoolExecutor(10, 20, 60,
                                      TimeUnit.SECONDS, queue);
                              executor.submit(() -> asyncJobService.submitJob(() -> {}, "sample job"));
